<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="97" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1301,1658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1301,1326]" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Medium sized (
<quantity box="[469,583,1302,1326]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="10.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.0">9–12 mm</quantity>
) species. Medial labral emargination shallow. Sides of pronotum mostly distinctly bordered except for anterior angles; base of pronotum strongly sinuate, thus posterior angles of pronotum produced backwards, acute (
<figureCitation box="[483,576,1373,1398]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1967,1989]" captionTargetBox="[230,1394,213,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1404,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. A) Nartus grapii (Gyllenhal, 1808), 11 mm, Germany; B) Rhantus atricolor (Aubé, 1838), 15 mm, Mexico; C) Rhantus frontalis (Marsham, 1802), 10.5 mm, Germany; D) Rhantus selkirki Jäch, Balke &amp; Michat, 2014, 6.6 mm, Chile." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/569190/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
, arrow). Elytral reticulation double, consisting of large polygonal meshes filled with fine polygonal cells. Setae on parameres distally acute. In contrast to most species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1293,1385,1410,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Rhantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1385,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Rhantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and related genera, both members of 
<taxonomicName box="[519,595,1447,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Nartus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[519,595,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Nartus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are totally black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1301,1658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1485,1510]" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Position</emphasis>
. In 
<bibRefCitation box="[345,612,1485,1510]" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" refString="Moriniere, J., Van Dam, M. H., Hawlitschek, O., Bergsten, J., Michat, M. C., Hendrich, L., Ribera, I., Toussaint, E. F. A. &amp; Balke, M. (2016) Phylogenetic niche conservatism explains an inverse latitudinal diversity gradient in freshwater arthropods. Scientific Reports, 6, 26340." type="journal article">
Morinière 
<emphasis box="[467,526,1485,1509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[626,702,1486,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Nartus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[626,702,1486,1509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Nartus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recovered as the sister group of 
<taxonomicName box="[1139,1231,1485,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Rhantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1139,1231,1485,1509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Rhantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as newly defined here, and we suggest that the original use of 
<taxonomicName box="[650,726,1522,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Nartus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[650,726,1522,1545]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Nartus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at generic rank is justified by our studies (
<figureCitation box="[1204,1269,1521,1546]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[341,1289,339,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[327,1304,339,1817]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic reconstruction of Colymbetinae relationships using different methods of phylogenetic inference (Bayesian, Maximum Likelihood, Parsimony, figure modified from Morinière et al. 2016 which contains more details on analytical procedures); node support for major backbone nodes indicated with asterisks: black meaning strong support, lighter shades of grey referring to increasingly weaker support. Distribution is coded in colour and ancestral areas were inferred using the software package BioGeoBEARS (details in Morinière et al. 2016). Notes: &quot; R. signatus JFern. &quot; refers to a specimen from Juan Fernandez Archipelago (originally described as R. kuscheli Guignot, 1952)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/569187/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="97">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
